lank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/675793/fire-statistics-data-tables-fire1403.xlsx</a></p><p>All local authorities hold a general reserve which provides contingency funding for any unexpected costs. As at March 2017, Merseyside Fire and Rescue Authority held 31.9 million in reserves (an increase of 14.1m), equivalent to 53.5% of their core spending power. This included 2m in the general reserve.</p><p> </p><p>Spending Review 2015 provided a firm, four-year settlement to local authorities including fire and rescue authorities, giving greater certainty of funding until the end of 2019/20. Funding information can be found in the link below.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/679611/Core_Spending_Power_Supporting_Information.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/679611/Core_Spending_Power_Supporting_Information.xlsx</a></p><p>Single purpose fire and rescue authorities will receive a 0.3% increase in core spending power over the four years of this spending review. The 2019 Spending Review will set overall local government resourcing from 2020-21.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","172443 ; 172444 ; 172445","2018-09-13T16:10:30.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971350/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971350/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-10","Merseyside Fire and Rescue Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government has any contingency funds which could be made available to the Merseyside Fire and Rescue Service.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","172446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971351","Department for Transport","false","2018-09-17","<p>The Department has had regular discussions with Network Rail about its commercial estate.</p><p> </p><p>On 10 September, Network Rail announced that it had agreed a 1.46bn sale with Telereal Trillium and Blackstone Property Partners for the sale of its commercial estate portfolio.</p><p> </p><p>Tenants existing rights have been safeguarded in this sale and current agreements between Network Rail and tenants will be fully honoured.</p><p> </p><p>The new owner has also agreed to a tenant charter including amongst other commitments to engage in an open and honest manner with their tenants and the community, ongoing transparency regarding publication of data on mix of tenants and the provision of an engagement officer. They have also undertaken to work with long-standing small business tenants that face financial pressure, including offering financial support.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-09-17T13:38:05.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971351/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971351/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-10","Network Rail: Bridges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department  has had with Network Rail on the effect of Network Rail's policies on railway arches on small businesses that are tenants.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","172423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971352","Treasury","false","2018-09-13","<p>The charge on disguised remuneration (DR) loans is targeted at artificial tax avoidance schemes where earnings were paid via a third party in the form of loans which in reality were never repaid.</p><p> </p><p>DR scheme users took home almost all of their pay tax-free. However, despite the claims made by promoters, these schemes never worked and the amounts paid were always taxable under the law at the time.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has decided that the charge on DR loans is the right way to ensure that everybody pays the taxes they owe and contributes towards the public-funded services from which they benefit.</p><p> </p><p>Restricting the charge only to DR loans entered into after Finance Act 2017 received Royal Assent would not be fair to ordinary taxpayers, who have always paid the right amount of tax and have not engaged in tax avoidance schemes.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-09-13T15:15:30.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971352/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971352/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-10","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will limit disguised remuneration loan charges to loans entered into after the Finance Act 2017 received Royal Assent; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","172456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971353","Home Office","false","2018-09-13","<p>We intend to assess this pilot fully before taking any decisions on future arrangements</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-09-13T15:49:28.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971353/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971353/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-10","Visas: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the announcement, New pilot scheme to bring 2,500 seasonal workers to UK farms, published on 6 September 2018, whether he has plans to introduce other sector specific visa schemes.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","172519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971354","Prime Minister","false","2018-09-13","<p>I refer Hon. Member to the Oral Statement I gave on 16 April 2018 on Syria, Official Report, Column 42</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2018-09-13T13:37:33.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971354/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971354/answer",,,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2018-09-10","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether she plans to seek parliamentary approval before any new airstrikes on Syria.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","172520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971355","Treasury","false","2018-09-17","<p>The government keeps all taxes under review as part of the Budget process, and we will continue to evaluate all alcohol duties, including beer duty, to ensure they are fair and efficient.</p><p> </p><p>This government remains clear in its support for consumers, pubs and breweries, and we have taken action to this end  meaning that the price of a pint of beer is 12p is lower than it otherwise would have been since 2013/14.</p><p> </p><p>However, we cannot ignore the cost to the Exchequer of successive freezes  equal to over 4 billion since 2013/14. Any assessment of the merits of further freezes or cuts needs to consider the resulting reduction in funds available for vital public services.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-09-17T13:51:15.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971355/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971355/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-10","Beer: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department plans to reduce beer duty.","false","Biography information for Mike Hill","Hartlepool","Mike Hill","172521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971356","Treasury","false","2018-09-18","<p>Though we have made no such assessment of the beer duty freeze announced at Autumn Budget 2017 on jobs and investment, this government remains clear in our support for the brewing and pubs sector and the important contribution it makes to employment and community life.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-09-18T10:22:21.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971356/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971356/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-10","Beer: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on (a) jobs and (b) investment in the brewing and pubs sector of the beer duty freeze announced in the Autumn Budget 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","172431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971357","Treasury","false","2018-09-18","<p>The beer duty freeze has resulted in the average pint of beer being taxed 2p less than it otherwise would have been had duties been uprated in line with RPI.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-09-18T10:19:44.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971357/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971357/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971357/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-10","Beer: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on beer prices of the beer duty freeze announced in the Autumn Budget 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","172432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971358","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-09-13","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government published the Litter Strategy for England in 2017, setting out our approach of applying best practice in education, enforcement and binfrastructure in order to deliver a substantial reduction in litter and littering within a generation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Litter Strategy sets out a number of proposals to improve enforcement against littering, including commitments to support councils in using new powers to issue fixed penalties for smallscale flytipping offences, and deliver guidance to promote proportionate and responsible enforcement. Alongside the Strategy, we also consulted on proposals to increase the fixed penalty for littering, and to give councils improved powers to take enforcement action against littering from vehicles.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Through the National Fly-tipping Prevention Group we have published guidance which sets out clearly the powers available to local authorities when tackling fly-tipping. It is the responsibility of local authorities to use the full range of enforcement powers available to them to tackle fly-tipping. The list of powers is online here: <a href="http://www.tacklingflytipping.com/Documents/NFTPG-CaseStudies/Fly-tipping-responsibilities-Guide-for-local-authorities-and-land-manage....pdf" target="_blank">http://www.tacklingflytipping.com/Documents/NFTPG-CaseStudies/Fly-tipping-responsibilities-Guide-for-local-authorities-and-land-manage....pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>With effect from April 2018, we have increased the maximum fixed penalty for littering from 80 to 150, and given councils in England new powers to tackle littering from vehicles. We have no plans to make further changes to the level of fixed penalties at this stage. It is for councils now to use these powers and some are already taking advantage of them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We have also recently consulted on improved guidance on the proportionate use of these enforcement powers, which we propose to incorporate into the statutory Code of Practice on Litter and Refuse. That consultation closed on 8 June and responses are currently being considered. We expect to publish the revised guidance later this year.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thrse Coffey","172466","2018-09-13T12:21:26.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971358/answer","Biography information for Dr Thrse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971358/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-09-10","Fly-tipping and Litter: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to encourage local authorities to impose fines for littering and flytipping.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","172465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971359","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-09-13","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government published the Litter Strategy for England in 2017, setting out our approach of applying best practice in education, enforcement and binfrastructure in order to deliver a substantial reduction in litter and littering within a generation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Litter Strategy sets out a number of proposals to improve enforcement against littering, including commitments to support councils in using new powers to issue fixed penalties for smallscale flytipping offences, and deliver guidance to promote proportionate and responsible enforcement. Alongside the Strategy, we also consulted on proposals to increase the fixed penalty for littering, and to give councils improved powers to take enforcement action against littering from vehicles.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Through the National Fly-tipping Prevention Group we have published guidance which sets out clearly the powers available to local authorities when tackling fly-tipping. It is the responsibility of local authorities to use the full range of enforcement powers available to them to tackle fly-tipping. The list of powers is online here: <a href="http://www.tacklingflytipping.com/Documents/NFTPG-CaseStudies/Fly-tipping-responsibilities-Guide-for-local-authorities-and-land-manage....pdf" target="_blank">http://www.tacklingflytipping.com/Documents/NFTPG-CaseStudies/Fly-tipping-responsibilities-Guide-for-local-authorities-and-land-manage....pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>With effect from April 2018, we have increased the maximum fixed penalty for littering from 80 to 150, and given councils in England new powers to tackle littering from vehicles. We have no plans to make further changes to the level of fixed penalties at this stage. It is for councils now to use these powers and some are already taking advantage of them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We have also recently consulted on improved guidance on the proportionate use of these enforcement powers, which we propose to incorporate into the statutory Code of Practice on Litter and Refuse. That consultation closed on 8 June and responses are currently being considered. We expect to publish the revised guidance later this year.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thrse Coffey","172465","2018-09-13T12:21:26.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971359/answer","Biography information for Dr Thrse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971359/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-09-10","Litter: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of increasing the maximum fine for littering.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","172466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971360","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-09-13","<p>Forestry investment zones are being developed to drive our long term woodland expansion aspirations. No estimate has been made of the contribution of individual forestry investment zones to the 11 million tree commitment.</p><p><br></p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thrse Coffey",,"2018-09-13T09:12:21.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971360/answer","Biography information for Dr Thrse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971360/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-09-10","Tree Planting: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many of the 11 million trees his Department plans to be planted this Parliament will be planted in the first pilot forestry investment zone in Cumbria.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","172410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971361","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-09-18","<p>The Forestry Commissions Corporate Plan 2018-19 describes how it aims to support the planting of more woodland in England. The Forestry Commissions current priority is to work with the sector to deliver the Governments manifesto commitment to plant 11 million trees this Parliament. This and further action by the Forestry Commission and others will contribute to increasing woodland in England in line with our aspiration of 12% cover by 2060, which would involve planting 180,000 hectares by end of 2042.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thrse Coffey",,"2018-09-18T12:28:07.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971361/answer","Biography information for Dr Thrse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971361/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-09-10","Tree Planting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department's target of planting 180,000 hectares of new woodland in England by the end of 2042 will be adopted as a corporate objective by Forestry Commission England.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","172411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971362","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-09-13","<p>Statistics on all known new planting of woodland and on the area of woodland in England are already published annually by the Forestry Commission in Forestry Statistics, available on the Forest Research website.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thrse Coffey",,"2018-09-13T12:28:15.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971362/answer","Biography information for Dr Thrse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971362/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-09-10","Tree Planting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether Forestry Commission England has plans to report on progress on achieving the Governments objective of planting 180,000 hectares of new woodland in England by the end of 2042 in its Annual Corporate Plan.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","172412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971363","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-09-17","<p>Maternity Allowance is paid by the Department to eligible self-employed and employed women who are not entitled to Statutory Maternity Pay.</p><p> </p><p>The standard rates of payment are reviewed annually during the uprating of social security benefits.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-09-17T14:21:19.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971363/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/971363/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-10","Maternity Allowance: Self-Employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment her Department has made of the adequacy of the provision of maternity allowance for self-employed people.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","172522"
